1,1,2,2-Tetrachloroethane: Cytochrome P450, family 1, subfamily A, polypeptide 1, delta cycle threshold
1,1,2,2-Tetrachloroethane (C2H2Cl4): Delta cycle threshold for Cytochrome P450, family 1, subfamily A, polypeptide 1 (cyp1a1). Cycle threshold is the PCR cycle number at which the fluorescent signal of the gene being amplified crosses the set threshold. Delta cycle threshold for cyp1a1 is the difference between the cycle threshold (Ct) of cyp1a1 gene expression and the cycle threshold (Ct) for the gene expression of the reference gene (e.g., beta-actin).
The total protein concentration within the cytosolic fraction of cells. The cytosol refers to the intracellular fluid or cytoplasmic matrix of a eukaryotic cell.

In a single cell gel electrophoresis assay (comet assay), olive tail moment is the product of the percentage of DNA in the tail and the distance between the intesity centroids of the head and tail along the x-axis (Olive, et al., 1990)

In a single cell gel electrophoresis assay (comet assay), percent tail DNA is the ratio of fluorescent intensity of the tail over the total fluorescent intensity of the head (nuclear core) and tail multiplied by 100.
In a single cell gel electrophoresis assay (comet assay), tail length is the distance of DNA migration from the body of the nuclear core
The amount of water that could be evaporated and transpired if there was sufficient water available.

Permittivity is a physical quantity that describes how an electric field affects, and is affected by a dielectric medium, and is determined by the ability of a material to polarize in response to the field, and thereby reduce the total electric field inside the material. Thus, permittivity relates to a material's ability to transmit (or "permit") an electric field.

pH is the measure of the acidity or alkalinity of a solution. pH is formally a measure of the activity of dissolved hydrogen ions (H+). Solutions in which the concentration of H+ exceeds that of OH- have a pH value lower than 7.0 and are known as acids.
